<DOC><DOCNO> AP890816-0153 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-16-89 1913EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     08-16 0494</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0508</SECOND><HEAD>Thunderstorms Extend From The Ohio Valley to The Ozarks</HEAD><TEXT>   Thunderstorms spread from southern Ohio to southeast Kansas andeastern Oklahoma and were scattered across the East and Gulf coasts,dampening the hopes of many Americans for a glimpse of Wednesdaynight's lunar eclipse.   In Oklahoma, the storms dumped up to 3{ inches of rain nearSasakwa, and flooded many rural roads across Seminole and Pontotoccounties. Street flooding was reported at Ada.   Heavy rain also fell in the Wichita, Kan., area, and St. Louis,Mo., got its first rain of the month. A thunderstorm produced strongwinds and small hail at Falmouth in northern Kentucky.   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered across the East Coastand Gulf Coast states. A thunderstorm brought .69 inches of rain in17 minutes at Port Arthur, Texas.   A tropical storm warning was issued for islands in the easternCaribbean as a depression moved westward from the Atlantic.   The depression, with maximum sustained winds of 35 mph, wasmoving at about 20 mph and some strengthening was expected byThursday afternoon, according to the National Hurricane Center inCoral Gables, Fla.   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDTincluded 1.06 inches at Chanute, Kan.; .74 inches at Wichita, Kan.;.94 inches at Beaumont and Port Arthur, Texas; .67 inches at MineralWells, Texas; and .59 inches at St. Louis, Mo.   Widely scattered showers and thunderstorms also developed in theafternoon across the Rockies, and were expected over the northernHigh Plains.   Those parts of the nation with a clear eastern sky were expectedto be able to view Wednesday night's lunar eclipse.   Temperatures were in the 70s and 80s across most of the nation inthe afternoon. Much of the northwestern states from Montana to thePacific Northwest had readings in the 60s. Temperatures were in thelower 90s over portions of the Eastern seaboard, the central GulfCoast and Texas.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 55degrees at Coeur d'Alene, Idaho, to 104 degrees at Needles, Calif.The low in the nation Wednesday morning was 31 degrees at Truckee,Calif.   Thursday's forecast called for numerous showers and thunderstormsover the central Gulf Coast region, southern Florida, and portionsof Virginia and West Virginia; and scattered showers andthunderstorms from the middle and south Atlantic Coast states acrossthe Tennessee Valley and Gulf Coast states to the southern Plains.Showers and thunderstorms were also expected across the Rockies andDakotas to western Minnesota.   High temperatures were expected in the 70s from the Great Lakesregion and upper Ohio Valley to northern New England, and fromnorthwest Montana to the Pacific Northwest and along the Californiacoast; and in the 80s to lower 90s over most of the rest of thenation. Temperatures were expected to reach near 100 degrees in theRio Grande Valley of Texas and over portions of Utah and theinterior valleys of California.</TEXT></DOC>